  "instructions": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "-- Make the Toasted Rice Powder --"
      },
      {
        "S": "Place 2 tbsp glutinous rice in a dry skillet or wok over medium heat. Do not add oil."
      },
      {
        "S": "Toast the rice, stirring or shaking constantly, for 5 to 8 minutes until the grains are deep golden brown and fragrant with a nutty, popcorn-like aroma."
      },
      {
        "S": "Remove from heat and let cool for 2 minutes."
      },
      {
        "S": "Grind the toasted rice in a mortar and pestle or spice grinder to a coarse powder, keeping some texture. Set aside."
      },
      {
        "S": "-- Marinate the Steak --"
      },
      {
        "S": "Whisk together 1 tbsp soy sauce, 1 tbsp oyster sauce, 1 tbsp neutral oil, 1 tbsp finely chopped palm sugar, 3 cloves minced garlic, and 1/4 tsp ground white pepper in a bowl."
      },
      {
        "S": "Pat 1 1/3 to 1 3/4 lb steak dry with paper towels, then coat evenly with the marinade."
      },
      {
        "S": "Cover and refrigerate for 30 minutes to 2 hours. Remove from the fridge 20 to 30 minutes before cooking to bring to room temperature."
      },
      {
        "S": "-- Cook the Steak (Grilling Option) --"
      },
      {
        "S": "Preheat your grill (charcoal preferred for smokiness) to high heat, about 450 to 500 degrees F."
      },
      {
        "S": "Oil the grill grates. Place the steak on the grill and cook undisturbed for 3 to 4 minutes per side for medium-rare (internal temp 125 to 130 degrees F), or 4 to 5 minutes per side for medium (140 degrees F)."
      },
      {
        "S": "Move the steak to direct high heat for the final 30 seconds per side for extra char."
      },
      {
        "S": "-- Cook the Steak (Pan-Searing Option) --"
      },
      {
        "S": "Heat 2 tbsp neutral oil in a heavy-bottomed skillet or cast-iron pan over high heat until the oil begins to shimmer and lightly smoke."
      },
      {
        "S": "Carefully lay the steak away from you into the pan. Sear for 3 to 4 minutes per side without moving, until a deep brown crust forms."
      },
      {
        "S": "Finish steaks thicker than 1 1/2 inches in a preheated 400 degree F oven for 3 to 5 minutes to reach desired doneness."
      },
      {
        "S": "-- Rest the Steak --"
      },
      {
        "S": "Transfer the steak to a cutting board and tent loosely with foil."
      },
      {
        "S": "Rest for 8 to 10 minutes to allow the juices to redistribute, keeping every slice succulent. Optionally reserve any resting juices to add to the dipping sauce."
      },
      {
        "S": "-- Make the Nam Jim Jaew Dipping Sauce --"
      },
      {
        "S": "Dissolve 1 tbsp finely chopped palm sugar in 2 tbsp fresh lime juice by stirring well in a mixing bowl."
      },
      {
        "S": "Add 2 tbsp fish sauce and 1 tbsp tamarind paste to the bowl and stir to combine."
      },
      {
        "S": "Add 1 to 2 tbsp toasted rice powder, 1 to 3 tsp Thai chili flakes, 1 thinly sliced small shallot, and 1 tbsp chopped fresh cilantro. Mix well."
      },
      {
        "S": "Taste and adjust the sauce: it should be sour first, then salty, sweet, and spicy. Add more lime for sourness, fish sauce for salt, sugar for sweetness, or chili for heat."
      },
      {
        "S": "-- Slice and Serve --"
      },
      {
        "S": "Slice the steak against the grain into strips approximately 1/4 inch thick."
      },
      {
        "S": "Arrange the steak slices on a plate or wooden board. Serve immediately with the nam jim jaew in a small dipping bowl, sticky rice, and fresh raw vegetables including cabbage wedges, cucumber, Thai basil, mint, and long beans."
      }
    ]
  },
  "notes": {
    "L": [
      {
        "S": "For a gluten-free version, substitute the soy sauce with tamari or coconut aminos and use a gluten-free oyster sauce."
      },
      {
        "S": "For a dairy-free and paleo variation, this recipe is naturally dairy-free. Ensure the oyster sauce and fish sauce brands are free of added gluten or dairy."
      },
      {
        "S": "Charcoal grilling is preferred for an authentic smoky flavor integral to the traditional dish."
      },
      {
        "S": "Flank steak is a more traditional, leaner option closer to the brisket cuts used in Isan. Slice very thin against the grain."
      },
      {
        "S": "Start with 1 tsp chili flakes for mild, 2 tsp for medium, and 3 tsp for authentically Thai heat."
      },
      {
        "S": "Leftover sliced steak keeps 2 days refrigerated. The sauce should be made fresh each time."
      }
    ]
  },
